<font color="#FF0000">MY  SHARED THOUGHTS.</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 23  2:17:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Saddness is always there.  Fond memories mixed with tragic memory, wrapped in tears and numbness.  The writing of these poems helped me... I hope they help you.<br><br>
From &quot;Scars and Stripes, Forever&quot; Copy 1990 by Edward Ramon<br><br>
&quot;Clinging&quot;<br><br>
In bold relief there clings one leaf<br>
    when all the others are scattered.<br>
And among those panes only one remains<br>
    while the others all are shattered.<br>
See, out of the all one stalk stands tall<br>
     over grain that litters the ground.<br>
The lonesome dove that circles above<br>
     gives birth to that mournful sound.<br>
The old barn door drags on the floor<br>
     with only one good hinge remaining.<br>
Now, my soldier's heart stands far apart,<br>
     alone in its sad refraining.<br>
No, all the tears of a thousand years<br>
     will not bring them back alive.<br>
I often wonder and deeply ponder...<br>
     &quot;Why did I have to survive?&quot;<br>
But as each friend fell, in that Asian hell,<br>
     they left me simply knowing,<br>
That regardless of the gait I meet by fate,<br>
     they knew that I would keep on going.<br>
So, I stand alone, here safe at home<br>
     with my red and swollen eyes.<br>
Feeling, &quot;they would never forgive, if I failed to live<br>
    what could have been their lives.&quot;<br><br>
&quot;You Must Live&quot;<br><br>
Mud was splashed upon his chin<br>
     and caked upon his chest.<br>
Yet, rips in his clothes were neatly sewn.<br>
     A sergeant must look his best.<br>
His rifle, clutched by his lifeless hand,<br>
     lay close to his bloody side.<br>
Spent cartridges were scattered everywhere,<br>
     he had fought well until he died.<br>
He stared at me with his reddeded eyes,<br>
     sunk deeply in his ashen face.<br>
The words he spoke, came not from his mouth,<br>
     but from far away someplace.<br>
&quot;Sir,&quot; he said, &quot;Don't look so sad.&quot;<br>
     but I couldn't hold back the tears.<br>
Death had crippled my youthful gait,<br>
     and had calloused my tender years.<br>
Reaching down with fumbling fingers,<br>
     I closed his reddened eyes.<br>
The stench of death and the tropic sun<br>
     had drawn a thousand flies.<br>
Leaning over, with trembling lips,<br>
     I kissed his sainted head.<br>
&quot;You must live for those that live,&quot;<br>
     is what he had quietly said.<br><br>
&quot;The Corpsman Fell&quot;<br><br>
The wounded corpsman fell on his back<br>
    and knew that he was dying.<br>
But, bloody fingers groped for his pack,<br>
    when he heard a young man crying.<br>
He dragged himself to the suffering man<br>
    and took measures to ease his strife.<br>
Working quickly, as a good medic can,<br>
    he managed to save a life.<br>
Finding the words that he should speak,<br>
    he consoled his wounded brother.<br>
While his eyes grew dim and his hands turned weak,<br>
    he crawled away to find another.<br>
If only he would have lain quite still,<br>
    while all those about him cried,<br>
He would have lived to come off that hill,<br>
    but some of his comrades would have died.<br>
So, when the choppers came to haul the out,<br>
    from that tragic battleground,<br>
desperate survivors began to cheer and shout,<br>
    but not the corpsman, who made no sound.<br><br>
&quot;Sinking Sampans&quot;<br><br>
In the strangest places, I see their faces<br>
     still lit by the rocket's glare.<br>
Little faces, so excited by the missiles I ignited<br>
     so amazed, yet unaware.<br>
And I recall with dread, while the rockets sped,<br>
     that I did not seem to care.<br>
I took no heeding, at the warheads speeding,<br>
     or at what would litter the air.<br>
Now, tired eyes roam, through the bloody foam,<br>
     recording what was there.<br>
In the reddened spume my eyes consume<br>
     a baby's lifeless stare.<br>
It seems right, somehow, that I suffer now<br>
     with a heart that is stripped and bare.<br>
While I struggle, in vain to ease the pain,<br>
     I find comfort fleetingly rare,<br>
For in the strangest places, I see childrens'<br>
     faces... still lit by the rocket's glare.<br><br>
&quot;Lay it Down&quot;<br><br>
Rain no longer floods my plate,<br>
     My feet are healed and dry.<br>
There is no fear nor festering hate<br>
     or smoke to block the sky.<br><br>
I have no filty paddies to wade<br>
     and no leeches shall pierce my skin.<br>
Farewell to the rotting jungle shade<br>
     and the trails that never end.<br><br>
Goodbye, to the scorpions and deadly snakes<br>
     that creep and slither about.<br>
Gone, are the mines and the punji stakes<br>
     and the need to scream and shout.<br><br>
I do not have to bag the dead<br>
     or pray for the bleeding to stop.<br>
I do not sleep in a muddy bed<br>
     nor fight for a lofty mountain top.<br><br>
There are no beating rotor blades<br>
     or villages to straff and burn.<br>
I no longer crawl through the steaming glades<br>
     expecting death at every turn.<br><br>
So long, to the murky water I drank<br>
     and the mosquitoes that ate me alive.<br>
I will not remember the corpses that stank<br>
     nor desperately grope to survive.<br><br>
Farewell to the flying shrapnel<br>
     that tore my brothers apart.<br>
I chose, intently, not to grapple<br>
     with forces that rent the heart.<br><br>
The war is over... or so it seems<br>
     but still I wear a frown.<br>
I still fight the war in ghostly dreams<br>
    and I shall... until I lay it down.<br><br>
&quot;I Believe&quot;<br><br>
I walk alone with pain in my stride<br>
    but still, I can walk.<br>
I talk around things that I keep inside<br>
    but still, I can talk.<br>
I try my best and often fail<br>
    but still, I can try.<br>
I cry sometimes to no avail<br>
    but still, I can cry.<br>
I hear the sounds of a desperate call<br>
    but still, I can hear.<br>
I fear the worst if I should fall<br>
    but still, I can fear.<br>
I live a life that is filled with despair<br>
    but still, I can live.<br>
I give my all for those who do not care<br>
    but still, I can give.<br>
I sleep with intrusions of madness and horror<br>
    but still, I can sleep.<br>
I weep alone in cascades of sorrow<br>
    but still, I can weep.<br>
I grope about like one blinded and wild<br>
    but still, I can grope.<br>
I hope for the hopeless like a frightened child<br>
    but still, I can hope.<br>
I grieve for the dead, though not enough<br>
    but still, I can grieve.<br>
I believe the way back is awfully tough<br>
    but still, I can believe.<br>

